3.Verify pressure is zero in isolated section.  If possible allow the system to stand for several hours or overnight to allow the residual liquid ammonia to vaporize.
4.After an appropriate period of time re-check the pressure for zero before opening the isolated section for maintenance. 

In the above two procedures, if all ammonia is transferred to a secure portion of the system or a temporary storage vessel the likeliness of a release should be minimal.

Contingency Planning

For emergency situations refer to procedures outlined the IIAR Manual Appendix 1, Emergency Discharge of Ammonia Refrigerant for more detail.  This manual covers discharge to either atmosphere or to a water diffusion system.  

Only under exceptional circumstances should ammonia be allowed to discharge without controls.  If discharge is necessary, it should be controlled by a water diffusion system. Use of a water diffusion system should include the following additional procedures:

A.Know the pathway that ammonia water will take in the event of overflow.  Never allow ammonia water to discharge to the storm water drainage system.

B.In advance of any routine or emergency activity that may require the discharge of ammonia water to the sewer system, arrange to meet with wastewater system operators, either local municipal or on-site.  Topics should include the following:

1.Ammonia system description, operation, and routine M&R procedures;
2.Ammonia characteristics and hazards, particularly in water solution;
3.Possible ammonia discharge scenarios, including emergency situations;
4.Determine if ammonia water must be neutralized and/or diluted before discharge to process drains;
5.Determine if ammonia water must be metered into process drains;
6.Inform the operators that you will notify them if and when a discharge is necessary;
